name: Sengkang Riverside Park
review_text:
Sengkang Riverside Park is calm and tranquil. Featuring a constructed wetland and rich biodiversity, it is a favourite of nature lovers.

Visitors can hike on the park‚Äôs many trails to view the manually planted marshes and get close to the inhabitants of the marshland. Home to many aquatic plants, the constructed wetland doubles up as a wildlife habitat and attracts a variety of mangrove birds and damselflies. Alternatively, embark on an educational journey to explore the fruit trees planted around the park. Besides common edible fruits such as star fruit, chiku and dragon fruit, you may even discover exotic fruits that cannot be found in local stalls and supermarkets. Visitors can also visit Singapore‚Äôs largest man-made wetland, PUB‚Äôs Sengkang Floating Island, which is located within the park.

name: Sengkang Riverside Park
review_text:
Another hidden gem in north east corner of Singapore.
A long stretch of lush green lawns for a jog, walk, cycle or just a photowalk. It has 2 sides to explore. One u can reach to sengkang riverside park by taking the LRT and get down at Kapung station and walk down. The other side u can cross over to and walk towards the Sengkang floating wetland which is another beautiful picturesque place during sunrise and sunset times. There is a small place for kids to play and also a nice floating boardwalk around which there are some interesting placards of plant names placed. If you get tired and hungry there is a small food court around and also Mc Donalds and Pastamania if you head towards the LRT station of Anchorvale st. Right near the sengkang swimming complex there is an indoor and outdoor seating food court where you can chill with a beer and good food.

name: Sengkang Riverside Park
review_text:
There is one part of the park under development as of May, slated for completion by 2nd half 2021.
This park is walkable from nearby LRT stations. I took to Renjong LRT and then walked.
The park is separated into 2 by a road. Very isolated park I would say, as there are very few people usually here.
A good place to picnic or spend time to appreciate nature.
This park can be quite "hilly" though, as there are many inclined slopes.
Other than pavilions, trees and grass patches, nothing much if you don't appreciate nature.
There is 1 restaurant though at the park near the road. It's called O'My Kampung. No dine in seats however. Food is halal and only takeaway allowed. Prices are slightly more expensive than usual.
Would come again for some privacy!

Weaver Ants everywhere, just well it's a park. And someone complaint that there are ants at the Dog Run, yes there is a fenced up area for dogs to run) Well. It's a park, open air park, with birds, ants, millipedes, centipedes, bees, mosquitoes and other critters...

No more Kite flying as it is near Paya Lebar Airbase and there is a sign put up by MINDEF.

Generally safe to jog but do be careful still during evenings and early morning. Some parts of it are not well lit.  Early morning runs and exercises are best as it is cooler.

name: Sengkang Riverside Park
review_text:
This is a sizable park which is a combination of 3 sections.
On the northwest section, this area is peaceful and quiet. Many fruit trees can be found here, the ones I recognize are mulberry, mango, chiku, jambu and rose apples. Many birds are also seen around this area, probably feeding on the fruits and insects.
While wandering around the park, I notice that there are many red ants nesting on the fruit trees, also spotted a beehive on one of the trees. Parents with young children should take note and take care.
On the Southwest section with the Floating wetlands, spotted 2 otters, lots of terrapins and fishes in the water. Had a bit of fun feeding bread to the fishes.
The Northeast section is busy with many people exercising.

name: Sengkang Riverside Park
review_text:
This park is near my home and I frequent this every morning (if I don't oversleep). Its a huge park and extends for more than 3Km in length and has a extensive pathways to run,jog etc. Its very green with a river (more like a canal) flowing right in the center.

The highlight of the park is the floating wooden bridge that joins the two sides of the river. Its really a sight.

Few things that could improve for this park is more seating and exercise areas. It really lacks a children's playing area.

The park is next to the stadium and Anchorvale CC and has a few restaurants. Also has a boating facility (kayaks mostly).

name: Sengkang Riverside Park
review_text:
It is a quiet and  beautiful park set by the banks of the former Punngol River now a  reservoir.There are fruit trees planted in the park not a common feature in most parks.There are also about 3 to 4 big ponds presented to look like small lakes. In the park  there is a structure with a cafe called "Mushroom Cafe". The park consist of two parts, seperated by a road.On week days it is quite empty,but on Sundays you can see quite alot of people having fun doing different activities there.

name: Sengkang Riverside Park
review_text:
A nice park with bridges over Sungei Punggol. Good place for walk and run. Suitable for family with children and dogs. Can walk (about 1.5hrs) or cycle all the way to Punggol Waterway, which is approximately 3Km distance. And if you hungry, you will find nice food at TenderBest at Sengkang or the coffeeshop at Punggol Bayview.

Part of the path to Punggol is closed for construction works. As such you cannot enjoy the river for 1 to 2 Km of the distance.
I give 4-stars for this park cause I think Marina Bay East Garden, Ang Mo Kio-Bishan, park Bt Batok Nature park and Sungei Buloh are the best.

review_text:
(Translated by Google) What a great place this little park is, and it's so close to my house. I've been shopping here for several years and always find something new. Let‚Äôs just talk about the trees found here. The only fruits I can recognize are mulberries, mangoes, water apples, guavas, cashews, and dragon fruits. There are several others that I don't know. You can walk back and forth on many small roads inside, a few small ponds, and see turtles, fish, dragonflies, and water snails. If you don‚Äôt like to walk, there is a restaurant here called mushroom, which is built in a high place with a high ceiling but no walls. It is often very windy and it is very cool to sit in. Drink a cup of tea, eat a little snack, and enjoy the breeze.
